The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Wednesday, May 26, 2004 				 UPA links Pak talks to terror
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 																								New Delhi, May 25: The new Congress-led regime in Delhi committed itself to peace with Pakistan and solving all outstanding issues through bilateral negotiations, but under an atmosphere free from the menace of terrorism and violence. 																								Quoting Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, foreign minister Natwar Singh spelt out the stand to his Pakistani counterpart Khursheed Mehmood Kasuri when the latter called this morning to congratulate him on assuming office. 																								During the seven-minute exchange, Singh recalled the conversation between Manmohan Singh and President Pervez Musharraf recently, in which the former conveyed support for the peace process and emphasised the need to continue in an atmosphere free from the menace of terrorism and violence. 																								Foreign ministry spokesperson Navtej Sarna said: Both ministers expressed their determination to continue and further expedite the present process in India-Pakistan relations building upon the support provided by the people in both countries. 																								In Islamabad, Kasuri said he looked forward to a serious and sustained engagement with the new Indian government while expressing confidence that the ongoing peace process would gain in strength. 																								I am confident that the process of peace that has been initiated between our two countries will gain strength under your able leadership, Kasuri told Singh. It gives me great pleasure to congratulate you most warmly on your appointment as the foreign minister of the Republic of India, he added. 																								While wishing Singh every success in the fulfilment of his important responsibilities, Kasuri said a serious and sustained engagement as in the interest of peace and stability in the region and held the potential of rich dividends for the people of the two countries.																								I also look forward to working together with you towards reinvigorating regional cooperation under the aegis of Saarc, Kasuri said. Putin calls Atal 																								Russian President Vladimir Putin today called up Atal Bihari Vajpayee to thank him warmly for his years-long cooperation and contribution in the development of a strategic partnership between India and Russia. 																								Both sides in their telephonic conversation expressed confidence that interaction of Russia and India as partners is the natural choice of the peoples and the bilateral relations will continue to further strengthen in the spirit of continuity, the Kremlin press service said in a statement. 
